class=3D"body main-article-body"><section class=3D"abstract" id=3D"abstract=
1"><h2 data-anchor-id=3D"abstract1"><a id=3D"abstract1-anchor" data-anchor-=
id=3D"abstract1" class=3D"usa-anchor"></a>Abstract</h2>
<p>Although sample size calculations play an essential role in health resea=
rch, published research often fails to report sample size selection. This s=
tudy aims to explain the importance of sample size calculation and to provi=
de considerations for determining sample size in a simplified manner. Appro=
aches to sample size calculation according to study design are presented wi=
th examples in health research. For sample size estimation, researchers nee=
d to (1) provide information regarding the statistical analysis to be appli=
ed, (2) determine acceptable precision levels, (3) decide on study power, (=
4) specify the confidence level, and (5) determine the magnitude of practic=
al significance differences (effect size). Most importantly, research team =
members need to engage in an open and realistic dialog on the appropriatene=
ss of the calculated sample size for the research question(s), available da=
ta records, research timeline, and cost. This study aims to further inform =
researchers and health practitioners interested in quantitative research, s=
o as to improve their knowledge of sample size calculation.</p>
<section id=3D"kwd-group1" class=3D"kwd-group"><p><strong>Keywords:</strong=
> effect size, power, regression analysis, sample size, study design</p></s=
ection></section><section class=3D"abstract" id=3D"abstract2"><hr class=3D"=
headless">
<p>This review aims to explain the importance of sample size calculation an=
d to provide considerations for determining sample size in a simplified man=
ner. Five elements essential in sample size calculation are discussed, and =
practical examples are used. This study aims to further inform researchers =
and health practitioners interested in quantitative research, so as to impr=
ove their knowledge of sample size calculation.</p>
<section class=3D"bt xbox font-sm" id=3D"jgf2600-blkfxd-0001"><p class=3D"i=
mg-box line-height-none margin-x-neg-2 tablet:margin-x-0 text-center"><img =
class=3D"graphic" src=3D"https://cdn.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/blobs/605f/100002=
62/533d24be2d3d/JGF2-24-72-g001.jpg" loading=3D"lazy" id=3D"jats-graphic-1"=
 height=3D"163" width=3D"461" alt=3D"graphic file with name JGF2-24-72-g001=
.jpg"></p></section></section><section id=3D"jgf2600-sec-0001"><h2 class=3D=
"pmc_sec_title" data-anchor-id=3D"jgf2600-sec-0001"><a id=3D"jgf2600-sec-00=
01-anchor" data-anchor-id=3D"jgf2600-sec-0001" class=3D"usa-anchor"></a>1. =
INTRODUCTION</h2>
<p>In the initial stage of planning a research study, sample size calculati=
on=E2=80=94or power calculation=E2=80=94answers the question, =E2=80=9CHow =
many participants or observations need to be included in this study?=E2=80=
=9D If the sample size is low, the research outcome might not be reproducib=
le.<a href=3D"https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC10000262/#jgf2600-bi=
b-0001" class=3D"usa-link" aria-describedby=3D"jgf2600-bib-0001" aria-expan=
ded=3D"false">
<sup>1</sup>
</a> Informal guidelines for sample size based on the experience of researc=
hers are used in most research studies and may be sufficient, as is the cas=
e in pilot studies.<a href=3D"https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC1000=
0262/#jgf2600-bib-0002" class=3D"usa-link" aria-describedby=3D"jgf2600-bib-=
0002" aria-expanded=3D"false">
<sup>2</sup>
</a>, <a href=3D"https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC10000262/#jgf2600=
-bib-0003" class=3D"usa-link" aria-describedby=3D"jgf2600-bib-0003" aria-ex=
panded=3D"false">
<sup>3</sup>
</a> However, when funding or institutional review board approval is reques=
ted, review committees often expect an explicit justification of the sample=
 size. An increasing number of academic journals have requested evidence of=
 sample size calculation or specific requirements to be provided in the met=
hod section of a manuscript, and the calculation can be part of a checklist=
 before submission to a journal.<a href=3D"https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/art=
icles/PMC10000262/#jgf2600-bib-0004" class=3D"usa-link" aria-describedby=3D=
"jgf2600-bib-0004" aria-expanded=3D"false">
<sup>4</sup>
</a>, <a href=3D"https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC10000262/#jgf2600=
-bib-0005" class=3D"usa-link" aria-describedby=3D"jgf2600-bib-0005" aria-ex=
panded=3D"false">
<sup>5</sup>
</a> In addition, when sample size calculation is not mentioned, reviewers =
may wonder whether the sample size is adequate.</p>
<p>Despite the many instructional materials available on sample size calcul=
ation, as well as statistical background knowledge being increasingly commo=
n among practitioners,<a href=3D"https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC1=
0000262/#jgf2600-bib-0006" class=3D"usa-link" aria-describedby=3D"jgf2600-b=
ib-0006" aria-expanded=3D"false">
<sup>6</sup>
</a> sample size calculation can be very challenging for researchers.<a hre=
f=3D"https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC10000262/#jgf2600-bib-0001" c=
lass=3D"usa-link" aria-describedby=3D"jgf2600-bib-0001" aria-expanded=3D"fa=
lse">
<sup>1</sup>
</a> In addition, although sample size calculation is requested as part of =
the method section of a manuscript, adding this requirement has not obvious=
ly increased the reporting of sample size.</p>
<p>The aim of this methods review is to present the importance of sample si=
ze calculation and to highlight factors worth considering when describing t=
he rationale for the selected sample size. The different equations for samp=
le sizes are not illustrated here, as they are beyond the scope of this rev=
iew. Instead, challenges relating to sample size calculations in health res=
earch are summarized.</p>
<p>The remainder of this paper is organized as follows. In Section&nbsp;<a =
href=3D"https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC10000262/#jgf2600-sec-0002=
" class=3D"usa-link">2</a>, some important terms are presented. Sections&nb=
sp;<a href=3D"https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC10000262/#jgf2600-se=
c-0007" class=3D"usa-link">3</a>, <a href=3D"https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/a=
rticles/PMC10000262/#jgf2600-sec-0010" class=3D"usa-link">6</a> discuss sam=
ple size calculations according to various types of study designs. Finally,=
 Section&nbsp;<a href=3D"https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC10000262/=
#jgf2600-sec-0011" class=3D"usa-link">7</a> offers some general recommendat=
ions.</p></section><section id=3D"jgf2600-sec-0002"><h2 class=3D"pmc_sec_ti=
tle" data-anchor-id=3D"jgf2600-sec-0002"><a id=3D"jgf2600-sec-0002-anchor" =
data-anchor-id=3D"jgf2600-sec-0002" class=3D"usa-anchor"></a>2. SAMPLE SIZE=
: WHAT TO UNDERSTAND?</h2>
<p>Sample size calculation involves several statistical terms, a selection =
of which is provided below in Table Table&nbsp;<a href=3D"https://pmc.ncbi.=
nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC10000262/#jgf2600-supitem-0001" class=3D"usa-link">=
S1</a>. In the following sections, the basic concepts are discussed, and de=
tailed guidance is provided for sample size calculation.</p>
<section id=3D"jgf2600-sec-0003"><h3 class=3D"pmc_sec_title">2.1. Expectati=
ons regarding sample size</h3>
<p>A sample size can be small, especially when investigating rare diseases =
or when the sampling technique is complicated and costly.<a href=3D"https:/=
/pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC10000262/#jgf2600-bib-0004" class=3D"usa-=
link" aria-describedby=3D"jgf2600-bib-0004" aria-expanded=3D"false">
<sup>4</sup>
</a>, <a href=3D"https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC10000262/#jgf2600=
-bib-0007" class=3D"usa-link" aria-describedby=3D"jgf2600-bib-0007" aria-ex=
panded=3D"false">
<sup>7</sup>
</a> Most academic journals do not place limitations on sample sizes.<a hre=
f=3D"https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC10000262/#jgf2600-bib-0008" c=
lass=3D"usa-link" aria-describedby=3D"jgf2600-bib-0008" aria-expanded=3D"fa=
lse">
<sup>8</sup>
</a> However, an insufficiently small sample size makes it challenging to r=
eproduce the results and may produce high false negatives, which in turn un=
dermine the scientific impact of the research. On the other hand, choosing =
to enlarge the sample size may be ethically unacceptable, particularly in P=
hase 1 studies, where human subjects are exposed to risks. Moreover, a very=
 large sample size may lead to <em>p</em>=E2=80=90values less than the sign=
ificance level even if the effect is not of practical or clinical importanc=
e (i.e., false positives).<a href=3D"https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/=
PMC10000262/#jgf2600-bib-0009" class=3D"usa-link" aria-describedby=3D"jgf26=
00-bib-0009" aria-expanded=3D"false">
<sup>9</sup>
</a> Hence, sample size calculation is important for striking a balance bet=
ween risk and benefit.<a href=3D"https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC1=
0000262/#jgf2600-bib-0010" class=3D"usa-link" aria-describedby=3D"jgf2600-b=
ib-0010" aria-expanded=3D"false">
<sup>10</sup>
</a> Researchers' focus should not be on producing large sample sizes. Inst=
ead, the focus should be on choosing an appropriately sized sample that ach=
ieves sufficient power so that statistical testing detects true positives, =
comprehensively reporting the analysis techniques and interpreting the resu=
lts in terms of <em>p</em>=E2=80=90values, effect size, and confidence inte=
rvals.<a href=3D"https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC10000262/#jgf2600=
-bib-0008" class=3D"usa-link" aria-describedby=3D"jgf2600-bib-0008" aria-ex=
panded=3D"false">
<sup>8</sup>
</a>, <a href=3D"https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC10000262/#jgf2600=
-bib-0011" class=3D"usa-link" aria-describedby=3D"jgf2600-bib-0011" aria-ex=
panded=3D"false">
<sup>11</sup>
</a>
</p></section><section id=3D"jgf2600-sec-0004"><h3 class=3D"pmc_sec_title">=
2.2. Sample size calculation using software programs</h3>
<p>Sample size calculation need not be done manually, and there are several=
 free=E2=80=90of=E2=80=90charge software tools that can assist in the calcu=
lation. For example, OpenEpi<a href=3D"https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/article=
s/PMC10000262/#jgf2600-bib-0012" class=3D"usa-link" aria-describedby=3D"jgf=
2600-bib-0012" aria-expanded=3D"false">
<sup>12</sup>
</a> (an open=E2=80=90source online calculator) and G*Power<a href=3D"https=
://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC10000262/#jgf2600-bib-0013" class=3D"us=
a-link" aria-describedby=3D"jgf2600-bib-0013" aria-expanded=3D"false">
<sup>13</sup>
</a> (a statistical software package) are commonly used for sample size cal=
culations. Wang and Ji<a href=3D"https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC1=
0000262/#jgf2600-bib-0014" class=3D"usa-link" aria-describedby=3D"jgf2600-b=
ib-0014" aria-expanded=3D"false">
<sup>14</sup>
</a> provide an online calculator for common studies in health research. PS=
 Power and Sample Size Calculation<a href=3D"https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/a=
rticles/PMC10000262/#jgf2600-bib-0015" class=3D"usa-link" aria-describedby=
=3D"jgf2600-bib-0015" aria-expanded=3D"false">
<sup>15</sup>
</a> or Sample Size Calculator<a href=3D"https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/artic=
les/PMC10000262/#jgf2600-bib-0016" class=3D"usa-link" aria-describedby=3D"j=
gf2600-bib-0016" aria-expanded=3D"false">
<sup>16</sup>
</a> are practical tools for power and sample size calculations in studies =
with dichotomous, continuous, or survival outcome measures. The support off=
ered by these tools varies in terms of the type of interface and the mathem=
atical formula or assumptions used for calculation.<a href=3D"https://pmc.n=
cbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC10000262/#jgf2600-bib-0017" class=3D"usa-link" =
aria-describedby=3D"jgf2600-bib-0017" aria-expanded=3D"false">
<sup>17</sup>
</a>, <a href=3D"https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC10000262/#jgf2600=
-bib-0018" class=3D"usa-link" aria-describedby=3D"jgf2600-bib-0018" aria-ex=
panded=3D"false">
<sup>18</sup>
</a>, <a href=3D"https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC10000262/#jgf2600=
-bib-0019" class=3D"usa-link" aria-describedby=3D"jgf2600-bib-0019" aria-ex=
panded=3D"false">
<sup>19</sup>
</a>, <a href=3D"https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC10000262/#jgf2600=
-bib-0020" class=3D"usa-link" aria-describedby=3D"jgf2600-bib-0020" aria-ex=
panded=3D"false">
<sup>20</sup>
</a>
</p></section><section id=3D"jgf2600-sec-0005"><h3 class=3D"pmc_sec_title">=
2.3. Statistical analysis to be used is important in sample size calculatio=
n</h3>
<p>Predominantly, the sample size should be determined based on statistical=
 analysis.<a href=3D"https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC10000262/#jgf=
2600-bib-0002" class=3D"usa-link" aria-describedby=3D"jgf2600-bib-0002" ari=
a-expanded=3D"false">
<sup>2</sup>
</a>, <a href=3D"https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC10000262/#jgf2600=
-bib-0021" class=3D"usa-link" aria-describedby=3D"jgf2600-bib-0021" aria-ex=
panded=3D"false">
<sup>21</sup>
</a>, <a href=3D"https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC10000262/#jgf2600=
-bib-0022" class=3D"usa-link" aria-describedby=3D"jgf2600-bib-0022" aria-ex=
panded=3D"false">
<sup>22</sup>
</a> The type of analysis should be closely related to the study design, st=
udy objective, research question(s), or primary research outcome. Most samp=
le size calculation software packages include the option to select the requ=
ired statistical test related to the response or outcome variable(s), with =
each test requiring a different sample size. Therefore, if a comparison bet=
ween two or more groups is required after estimating the frequency of a cer=
tain attribute in the population, the calculated sample size should be adju=
sted, in order to account for the types of statistical tests to be used in =
the comparison. This ensures that the final sample size is appropriately su=
ited to the study's main objective(s) or hypotheses.</p></section><section =
id=3D"jgf2600-sec-0006"><h3 class=3D"pmc_sec_title">2.4. When possible, det=
ermine the effect size</h3>
<p>In studies examining the effect of an intervention/exposure or the diffe=
rence(s) between two or more groups, the effect size must first be determin=
ed, in order to calculate an appropriate sample size. The effect size is de=
fined as the minimum effect an intervention must have in order to be consid=
ered clinically or practically significant.<a href=3D"https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.=
nih.gov/articles/PMC10000262/#jgf2600-bib-0023" class=3D"usa-link" aria-des=
cribedby=3D"jgf2600-bib-0023" aria-expanded=3D"false">
<sup>23</sup>
</a> This is considered the most challenging step in sample size calculatio=
n. When the effect is small, identifying it and reaching an acceptable leve=
l of power requires a large sample. When the effect is large, it is easily =
identifiable; hence, a smaller sample size is sufficient.</p>
<p>The size effect is mostly determined by experience or judgment.<a href=
=3D"https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC10000262/#jgf2600-bib-0024" cl=
ass=3D"usa-link" aria-describedby=3D"jgf2600-bib-0024" aria-expanded=3D"fal=
se">
<sup>24</sup>
</a> It can also be estimated from previously implemented, well=E2=80=90des=
igned studies (such as meta=E2=80=90analyze; see, for example, Thalheimer a=
nd Cook<a href=3D"https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC10000262/#jgf260=
0-bib-0025" class=3D"usa-link" aria-describedby=3D"jgf2600-bib-0025" aria-e=
xpanded=3D"false">
<sup>25</sup>
</a> for a simplified illustration on how to determine effect size from pub=
lished research). An initial pilot study may determine the effect size for =
start=E2=80=90up studies if accompanied by conversations with experts in th=
e field that provide useful information on adequate value for the effect si=
ze. In a pilot investigation, sample size calculation may not be required f=
or the pilot sample.<a href=3D"https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC100=
00262/#jgf2600-bib-0026" class=3D"usa-link" aria-describedby=3D"jgf2600-bib=
-0026" aria-expanded=3D"false">
<sup>26</sup>
</a> An important approach worth considering here involves enrolling pilot =
study participants based on the inclusion and exclusion criteria of the pla=
nned larger study and then testing the feasibility of the methods.<a href=
=3D"https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC10000262/#jgf2600-bib-0027" cl=
ass=3D"usa-link" aria-describedby=3D"jgf2600-bib-0027" aria-expanded=3D"fal=
se">
<sup>27</sup>
</a>, <a href=3D"https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC10000262/#jgf2600=
-bib-0028" class=3D"usa-link" aria-describedby=3D"jgf2600-bib-0028" aria-ex=
panded=3D"false">
<sup>28</sup>
</a>
</p>
<p>Various solutions have been proposed for cases where effect sizes cannot=
 be determined. Cohen<a href=3D"https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC10=
000262/#jgf2600-bib-0029" class=3D"usa-link" aria-describedby=3D"jgf2600-bi=
b-0029" aria-expanded=3D"false">
<sup>29</sup>
</a> recommends using small, medium, and large effect sizes instead of spec=
ific values (i.e., standardized or unit=E2=80=90free effect size). For exam=
ple, when the mean difference between two groups is of interest, and indepe=
ndent samples t=E2=80=90test is to be used, the standardized effect size is=
 calculated as: </p>
<table class=3D"disp-formula p" id=3D"jgf2600-disp-0001"><tbody><tr><td cla=
ss=3D"formula"><mjx-container class=3D"CtxtMenu_Attached_0" tabindex=3D"0" =
ctxtmenu_counter=3D"0"><mjx-lazy data-mjx-lazy=3D"0"></mjx-lazy></mjx-conta=
iner></td></tr></tbody></table>
<p>The difference between the two means is the difference in practical impo=
rtance, and the standard deviation of the response is often estimated from =
similar previous studies.</p>
<p>Figure&nbsp;<a href=3D"https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC10000262=
/#jgf2600-fig-0001" class=3D"usa-link">1</a> illustrates that a sample size=
 can be based on a range of standardized effect sizes and powers (e.g., <em=
>d</em>&nbsp;=3D&nbsp;0.2 [small], 0.5 [medium], or 0.8 [large]). If the ai=
m is to compare the mean difference between two groups, and an effect size =
of 0.5 (medium) is used, the total sample size required to reach a power of=
 80% is 128 participants. Hence, 64 participants are included in each group=
.</p>
<figure class=3D"fig xbox font-sm" id=3D"jgf2600-fig-0001"><h4 class=3D"obj=
_head">FIGURE 1.</h4>
<p class=3D"img-box line-height-none margin-x-neg-2 tablet:margin-x-0 text-=
center"><img class=3D"graphic" src=3D"https://cdn.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/blob=
s/605f/10000262/1d1a14f6adbb/JGF2-24-72-g003.jpg" loading=3D"lazy" id=3D"ja=
ts-graphic-3" height=3D"217" width=3D"614" alt=3D"FIGURE 1"></p>
<div class=3D"p text-right font-secondary"><a href=3D"https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.=
nih.gov/articles/PMC10000262/figure/jgf2600-fig-0001/" class=3D"usa-link" t=
arget=3D"_blank" rel=3D"noopener noreferrer">Open in a new tab</a></div>
<figcaption><p>G*power sample size software is used. Tail(s)&nbsp;=3D&nbsp;=
two: Two=E2=80=90tailed <em>t</em>=E2=80=90test. Allocation ratio N2/N1: In=
tended relative number of participants in each of the comparison groups (e.=
g., 1 or 2). <em>=CE=B1</em> err prob: The probability of type I error&nbsp=
;=3D&nbsp;0.05. <em>=CE=B2</em> err prob: The probability of type II error.=
</p></figcaption></figure><p>By contrast, for a small effect, the total sam=
ple size required is 788 patients, with 394 patients in each group. The use=
 of such arbitrary values is common in sample size calculations.<a href=3D"=
https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC10000262/#jgf2600-bib-0030" class=
=3D"usa-link" aria-describedby=3D"jgf2600-bib-0030" aria-expanded=3D"false"=
>
<sup>30</sup>
</a> Although these values do not admit biological explanations, they are c=
onsidered to have meaningful effects in most comparisons. However, research=
ers must note that these are arbitrary values, and must use their judgment =
to assess whether these values are acceptable in their field of research.<a=
 href=3D"https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC10000262/#jgf2600-bib-002=
4" class=3D"usa-link" aria-describedby=3D"jgf2600-bib-0024" aria-expanded=
=3D"false">
<sup>24</sup>
</a>, <a href=3D"https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC10000262/#jgf2600=
-bib-0031" class=3D"usa-link" aria-describedby=3D"jgf2600-bib-0031" aria-ex=
panded=3D"false">
<sup>31</sup>
</a>
</p></section></section><section id=3D"jgf2600-sec-0007"><h2 class=3D"pmc_s=
ec_title" data-anchor-id=3D"jgf2600-sec-0007"><a id=3D"jgf2600-sec-0007-anc=
hor" data-anchor-id=3D"jgf2600-sec-0007" class=3D"usa-anchor"></a>3. SAMPLE=
 SIZES FOR DESCRIPTIVE STUDIES</h2>
<p>A descriptive study is =E2=80=9Cconcerned with and designed only to desc=
ribe the existing distribution of variables, without regard to causal or ot=
her hypothesis.=E2=80=9D<a href=3D"https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PM=
C10000262/#jgf2600-bib-0032" class=3D"usa-link" aria-describedby=3D"jgf2600=
-bib-0032" aria-expanded=3D"false">
<sup>32</sup>
</a> Such studies include case reports, case series, and cross=E2=80=90sect=
ional (prevalence) studies.<a href=3D"https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles=
/PMC10000262/#jgf2600-bib-0033" class=3D"usa-link" aria-describedby=3D"jgf2=
600-bib-0033" aria-expanded=3D"false">
<sup>33</sup>
</a> In the latter, the objective is to describe a health phenomenon in a p=
opulation at a particular point in time. The main parameter of interest is =
proportion\prevalence, where the variable of interest is a categorical vari=
able. In descriptive studies, the research could also be interested in the =
mean, where the variable of interest is a continuous response variable. For=
 example, studies estimating the average age of children with asthma visiti=
ng the emergency room in a given year, or the prevalence of hyponatremia am=
ong the elderly in a tertiary care center, are descriptive in nature. The s=
teps for sample size calculation in such descriptive studies are provided i=
n Figure&nbsp;<a href=3D"https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC10000262/=
#jgf2600-fig-0002" class=3D"usa-link">2</a>.</p>
<figure class=3D"fig xbox font-sm" id=3D"jgf2600-fig-0002"><h3 class=3D"obj=
_head">FIGURE 2.</h3>
<p class=3D"img-box line-height-none margin-x-neg-2 tablet:margin-x-0 text-=
center"><img class=3D"graphic" src=3D"https://cdn.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/blob=
s/605f/10000262/4df2b9db39e3/JGF2-24-72-g002.jpg" loading=3D"lazy" id=3D"ja=
ts-graphic-5" height=3D"111" width=3D"614" alt=3D"FIGURE 2"></p>
<div class=3D"p text-right font-secondary"><a href=3D"https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.=
nih.gov/articles/PMC10000262/figure/jgf2600-fig-0002/" class=3D"usa-link" t=
arget=3D"_blank" rel=3D"noopener noreferrer">Open in a new tab</a></div>
<figcaption><p>Elements of sample size calculation for descriptive studies.=
</p></figcaption></figure><p>For example, a 95% confidence level indicates =
that the sample mean will not differ by more than a certain value from the =
true population mean in 95% of the repeatedly withdrawn samples from the sa=
me population. The margin of error (MoE) is a measure of the precision of a=
n estimate. The smaller the allowed MoE, the larger the precision of our es=
timates and the larger the sample size. Note that the confidence interval&n=
bsp;=3D&nbsp;estimate of value of interest =C2=B1 MoE. For example, if the =
prevalence of burnout is 15% in a sample of residents, then, for the larger=
 population, it is estimated to be between 5% and 25% (allowing MoE of 10% =
on both sides). The standard deviation (SD) and the estimate of proportion =
can be obtained from previous studies. If no information regarding the SD i=
s available, researchers can collect a pilot sample to estimate the value o=
f SD, and use <span xmlns:mml=3D"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><mjx-c=
ontainer class=3D"CtxtMenu_Attached_0" tabindex=3D"0" ctxtmenu_counter=3D"1=
"><mjx-lazy data-mjx-lazy=3D"1"></mjx-lazy></mjx-container></span>, where <=
em>n</em> is the number of observations in the pilot study.<a href=3D"https=
://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC10000262/#jgf2600-bib-0034" class=3D"us=
a-link" aria-describedby=3D"jgf2600-bib-0034" aria-expanded=3D"false">
<sup>34</sup>
</a> If that proportion is unknown, it is best to use a proportion close to=
 what is expected; otherwise, a value of 0.5 is assumed to give a sufficien=
tly large sample size.<a href=3D"https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC1=
0000262/#jgf2600-bib-0035" class=3D"usa-link" aria-describedby=3D"jgf2600-b=
ib-0035" aria-expanded=3D"false">
<sup>35</sup>
</a> However, this value is appropriate if the actual population proportion=
 is between 10% and 90%; otherwise (for example, in the case of rare or com=
mon disease), caution should be taken when substituting the proportion, as =
a significantly larger sample size is required.<a href=3D"https://pmc.ncbi.=
nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC10000262/#jgf2600-bib-0036" class=3D"usa-link" aria=
-describedby=3D"jgf2600-bib-0036" aria-expanded=3D"false">
<sup>36</sup>
</a>
</p>
<p>Note that population size is not needed as an input in most sample size =
calculations. The population can be defined by various elements, such as ge=
ographical, time frame, or social aspects. For example, if the prevalence o=
f infection in a hospital's intensive care unit (ICU) department during the=
 period between 2005 and 2012 is to be estimated, then the population is al=
l the patients admitted to ICU during that period. In most studies, we aim =
to generalize the results to a larger population, although we are restricte=
d to observing a specific population. Therefore, when estimating the sample=
 size, population size is rarely important in medical research.<a href=3D"h=
ttps://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC10000262/#jgf2600-bib-0037" class=
=3D"usa-link" aria-describedby=3D"jgf2600-bib-0037" aria-expanded=3D"false"=
>
<sup>37</sup>
</a> However, if the population is limited (e.g., in a study that evaluates=
 an academic program, where the population is all students enrolled in the =
program), then the sample size equations can be adjusted for the population=
 size.<a href=3D"https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC10000262/#jgf2600=
-bib-0037" class=3D"usa-link" aria-describedby=3D"jgf2600-bib-0037" aria-ex=
panded=3D"false">
<sup>37</sup>
</a>, <a href=3D"https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC10000262/#jgf2600=
-bib-0038" class=3D"usa-link" aria-describedby=3D"jgf2600-bib-0038" aria-ex=
panded=3D"false">
<sup>38</sup>
</a>, <a href=3D"https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC10000262/#jgf2600=
-bib-0039" class=3D"usa-link" aria-describedby=3D"jgf2600-bib-0039" aria-ex=
panded=3D"false">
<sup>39</sup>
</a> The size of a finite population can be obtained from a database or rec=
ords, or based on experience in the field, and is included in the sample si=
ze calculation.</p></section><section id=3D"jgf2600-sec-0008"><h2 class=3D"=
pmc_sec_title" data-anchor-id=3D"jgf2600-sec-0008"><a id=3D"jgf2600-sec-000=
8-anchor" data-anchor-id=3D"jgf2600-sec-0008" class=3D"usa-anchor"></a>4. S=
AMPLE SIZE FOR STUDIES COMPARING TWO GROUPS</h2>
<p>There are two main types of study in health research: observational and =
experimental. An important distinction between the two is that, in an obser=
vational study, the researcher does not impose any intervention and observe=
s only to assess a current condition. In experimental studies, an intervent=
ion is performed/conducted, and its results are observed. When the aim is t=
o compare two groups (intervention/control), the number of study participan=
ts should be equally divided between both groups, so as to attain the maxim=
um power for the given sample size. Note, however, that this point is limit=
ed to interventional studies and does not apply to observational studies (p=
rospective vs. retrospective). The minimum sample size per group must be ca=
lculated based on the statistical test used. However, in some fields of stu=
dy, such as pharmacology or biological research, a minimum of five per grou=
p is recommended and considered acceptable by academic journals in the fiel=
d.<a href=3D"https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC10000262/#jgf2600-bib=
-0004" class=3D"usa-link" aria-describedby=3D"jgf2600-bib-0004" aria-expand=
ed=3D"false">
<sup>4</sup>
</a> Recommendations for minimum sample sizes for clinical studies suggest =
having at least 100 in each group.<a href=3D"https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/a=
rticles/PMC10000262/#jgf2600-bib-0040" class=3D"usa-link" aria-describedby=
=3D"jgf2600-bib-0040" aria-expanded=3D"false">
<sup>40</sup>
</a> However, recent advances in sample size calculation have challenged th=
ese recommendations and have investigated the potential of simulation=E2=80=
=90based methods.<a href=3D"https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC100002=
62/#jgf2600-bib-0041" class=3D"usa-link" aria-describedby=3D"jgf2600-bib-00=
41" aria-expanded=3D"false">
<sup>41</sup>
</a>, <a href=3D"https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC10000262/#jgf2600=
-bib-0042" class=3D"usa-link" aria-describedby=3D"jgf2600-bib-0042" aria-ex=
panded=3D"false">
<sup>42</sup>
</a>
</p>
<p>Dividing participants equally between both groups might not be possible,=
 for several reasons, e.g., costs or limited data on the treatment group in=
 retrospective studies. In such cases, uneven groups are the best option at=
 hand where the researcher will opt to increase the sample in one group (e.=
g., control) with available data.<a href=3D"https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/ar=
ticles/PMC10000262/#jgf2600-bib-0043" class=3D"usa-link" aria-describedby=
=3D"jgf2600-bib-0043" aria-expanded=3D"false">
<sup>43</sup>
</a> Attention should be paid to the statistical data analysis to be used<a=
 href=3D"https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC10000262/#jgf2600-bib-004=
4" class=3D"usa-link" aria-describedby=3D"jgf2600-bib-0044" aria-expanded=
=3D"false">
<sup>44</sup>
</a> and the method for reporting results. <em>p</em>=E2=80=90values are ge=
nerally large (above 0.05) in such cases,<a href=3D"https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.ni=
h.gov/articles/PMC10000262/#jgf2600-bib-0045" class=3D"usa-link" aria-descr=
ibedby=3D"jgf2600-bib-0045" aria-expanded=3D"false">
<sup>45</sup>
</a> so reporting effect sizes<a href=3D"https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/artic=
les/PMC10000262/#jgf2600-bib-0029" class=3D"usa-link" aria-describedby=3D"j=
gf2600-bib-0029" aria-expanded=3D"false">
<sup>29</sup>
</a> and mean or median with confidence intervals can be more effective in =
conveying the practical importance of the results. All in all, increasing t=
he sample size increases the precision of estimates, so it is important to =
report these measures.</p></section><section id=3D"jgf2600-sec-0009"><h2 cl=
ass=3D"pmc_sec_title" data-anchor-id=3D"jgf2600-sec-0009"><a id=3D"jgf2600-=
sec-0009-anchor" data-anchor-id=3D"jgf2600-sec-0009" class=3D"usa-anchor"><=
/a>5. PROBABILITY AND NONPROBABILITY SAMPLING</h2>
<p>There are two types of sampling methods in research: probability (random=
) and nonprobability (nonrandom). In a probability sample, each unit has a =
known chance or probability of being selected. By contrast, in nonprobabili=
ty sampling, units are withdrawn or chosen without specific probabilities. =
Probability sampling includes simple random sampling, systematic sampling, =
and stratified sampling. Nonprobability sampling includes convenience sampl=
ing and quota sampling.</p>
<p>Probability sampling has the advantages of higher generalizability, grea=
ter representativeness of the population, and lower response bias than nonp=
robability sampling.<a href=3D"https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC100=
00262/#jgf2600-bib-0046" class=3D"usa-link" aria-describedby=3D"jgf2600-bib=
-0046" aria-expanded=3D"false">
<sup>46</sup>
</a> However, nonprobability sampling is the most commonly adopted type of =
sampling in clinical studies, survey statistics, and social research, due t=
o its low=E2=80=90 to no=E2=80=90cost or for ethical reasons.<a href=3D"htt=
ps://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC10000262/#jgf2600-bib-0047" class=3D"=
usa-link" aria-describedby=3D"jgf2600-bib-0047" aria-expanded=3D"false">
<sup>47</sup>
</a>, <a href=3D"https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC10000262/#jgf2600=
-bib-0048" class=3D"usa-link" aria-describedby=3D"jgf2600-bib-0048" aria-ex=
panded=3D"false">
<sup>48</sup>
</a>, <a href=3D"https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC10000262/#jgf2600=
-bib-0049" class=3D"usa-link" aria-describedby=3D"jgf2600-bib-0049" aria-ex=
panded=3D"false">
<sup>49</sup>
</a>, <a href=3D"https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC10000262/#jgf2600=
-bib-0050" class=3D"usa-link" aria-describedby=3D"jgf2600-bib-0050" aria-ex=
panded=3D"false">
<sup>50</sup>
</a> While calculating a sample size is important for the generalizability =
of results, estimating a sample size when using nonprobability sampling cou=
ld be irrelevant, as convenience sampling is likely to generate nongenerali=
zable results, which preclude statistical inference to the larger populatio=
n. As an alternative, researchers should include as many subjects as possib=
le<a href=3D"https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC10000262/#jgf2600-bib=
-0051" class=3D"usa-link" aria-describedby=3D"jgf2600-bib-0051" aria-expand=
ed=3D"false">
<sup>51</sup>
</a> from the different subgroups and demographics. The quota sampling appr=
oach=E2=80=94or sample matching=E2=80=94might well be applied to minimize t=
he selection bias often associated with nonprobability sampling.<a href=3D"=
https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC10000262/#jgf2600-bib-0052" class=
=3D"usa-link" aria-describedby=3D"jgf2600-bib-0052" aria-expanded=3D"false"=
>
<sup>52</sup>
</a> This is particularly useful if the hypothesis states that the main out=
come of interest differs based on specific factors or exposure, such as gen=
der or age group. The use of replication research studies to validate the r=
esults of nonprobability sampling is also encouraged as a strategy for ensu=
ring generalizability.<a href=3D"https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC1=
0000262/#jgf2600-bib-0053" class=3D"usa-link" aria-describedby=3D"jgf2600-b=
ib-0053" aria-expanded=3D"false">
<sup>53</sup>
</a> The methods section of a manuscript should include the number of subje=
cts invited to participate or the size of target population (if known) and =
the number of participants instead of an actual sample size calculation.<a =
href=3D"https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC10000262/#jgf2600-bib-0049=
" class=3D"usa-link" aria-describedby=3D"jgf2600-bib-0049" aria-expanded=3D=
"false">
<sup>49</sup>
</a> For a review on the inferential data analysis methods for nonprobabili=
ty sampling, see Buelens, Burger, and van den Brakel,<a href=3D"https://pmc=
.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC10000262/#jgf2600-bib-0046" class=3D"usa-link=
" aria-describedby=3D"jgf2600-bib-0046" aria-expanded=3D"false">
<sup>46</sup>
</a> who applied machine learning methods in order to enhance the represent=
ativeness of the beforementioned sampling.</p></section><section id=3D"jgf2=
600-sec-0010"><h2 class=3D"pmc_sec_title" data-anchor-id=3D"jgf2600-sec-001=
0"><a id=3D"jgf2600-sec-0010-anchor" data-anchor-id=3D"jgf2600-sec-0010" cl=
ass=3D"usa-anchor"></a>6. SAMPLE SIZE CALCULATION FOR REGRESSION ANALYSIS</=
h2>
<p>Correlation or regression analysis is used in studies aiming to examine =
associations between a set of independent variables and a response variable=
. Failing to include an appropriate number of observations leads to an insu=
fficient sample size, in which case regression might overfit the data.<a hr=
ef=3D"https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC10000262/#jgf2600-bib-0054" =
class=3D"usa-link" aria-describedby=3D"jgf2600-bib-0054" aria-expanded=3D"f=
alse">
<sup>54</sup>
</a> This means that, while the results may be valid for the study's datase=
t, they cannot be generalized to the population. In addition, estimates of =
regression coefficients are likely to be biased from true values, and the c=
onfidence intervals are large.<a href=3D"https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/artic=
les/PMC10000262/#jgf2600-bib-0001" class=3D"usa-link" aria-describedby=3D"j=
gf2600-bib-0001" aria-expanded=3D"false">
<sup>1</sup>
</a>, <a href=3D"https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC10000262/#jgf2600=
-bib-0011" class=3D"usa-link" aria-describedby=3D"jgf2600-bib-0011" aria-ex=
panded=3D"false">
<sup>11</sup>
</a> All these factors adversely affect statistical power. For regression a=
nalysis, several theories on sample size calculation have been provided in =
the literature regarding the use of logistic or linear regression for data =
fitting.<a href=3D"https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC10000262/#jgf26=
00-bib-0055" class=3D"usa-link" aria-describedby=3D"jgf2600-bib-0055" aria-=
expanded=3D"false">
<sup>55</sup>
</a>, <a href=3D"https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC10000262/#jgf2600=
-bib-0056" class=3D"usa-link" aria-describedby=3D"jgf2600-bib-0056" aria-ex=
panded=3D"false">
<sup>56</sup>
</a>, <a href=3D"https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC10000262/#jgf2600=
-bib-0057" class=3D"usa-link" aria-describedby=3D"jgf2600-bib-0057" aria-ex=
panded=3D"false">
<sup>57</sup>
</a>
</p>
<p>The number of predictors is important for sample size calculation in reg=
ression analysis. A larger sample size is required for a higher number of p=
redictors. In cases where interaction terms have more than two predictors, =
the number of interaction terms and the degree of interaction can become la=
rge. When the sample size is not large enough to conduct a similar regressi=
on analysis, one might add only important interaction terms with a large ef=
fect or use practical judgment to form the interaction terms.</p>
<p>Another important element in sample size calculation is the <em>R</em>=
=E2=80=90squared, defined as the measure of the strength of association bet=
ween the regression model and the response; it is also defined as the propo=
rtion of the variance in the response that is explained collectively by the=
 independent variables.<a href=3D"https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC=
10000262/#jgf2600-bib-0058" class=3D"usa-link" aria-describedby=3D"jgf2600-=
bib-0058" aria-expanded=3D"false">
<sup>58</sup>
</a> Calculating the sample size required for multiple regression analysis =
is equivalent to ascertaining the number of subjects to be enrolled to prod=
uce an acceptable <em>R</em>=E2=80=90squared or goodness=E2=80=90of=E2=80=
=90fit. Multiple regression analysis aims to determine whether a variable i=
s significantly associated with the outcome after controlling for all the o=
ther predictors. For purposes of estimating the effect size in multiple reg=
ressions of each variable, an assumption is made regarding the value of the=
 <em>R</em>=E2=80=90squared, because the exact estimates of regression coef=
ficients of these variables are unknown. It is then possible to calculate C=
ohen's <em>f</em>
<sup>2</sup> effect size, which is defined as the ratio of the proportion o=
f variance accounted for relative to the proportion of a variable unaccount=
ed for, where <em>f</em>
<sup>2</sup> is classified as small, medium, or large (<em>f</em>
<sup>2</sup>&nbsp;=3D=E2=80=890.02, 0.15 or 0.35, respectively) effect size=
s.<a href=3D"https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC10000262/#jgf2600-bib=
-0029" class=3D"usa-link" aria-describedby=3D"jgf2600-bib-0029" aria-expand=
ed=3D"false">
<sup>29</sup>
</a>
</p>
<p>Calculating sample size on the assumption that regression analysis is to=
 be used is not practical in many cases. For example, in any study, there m=
ay be more than one multiple regression model, and estimating the sample si=
ze for each model is not practical. Although it is common practice to estim=
ate a sample size sufficient to estimate the minimum effect size, a minimum=
 effect size might not be identifiable in some cases. Hence, researchers ha=
ve often relied on =E2=80=9Crules=E2=80=90of=E2=80=90thumb=E2=80=9D to dete=
rmine approximate sample sizes. For example, one of the considered rules=E2=
=80=90of=E2=80=90thumb calls for 10 observations per variable.<a href=3D"ht=
tps://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC10000262/#jgf2600-bib-0059" class=3D=
"usa-link" aria-describedby=3D"jgf2600-bib-0059" aria-expanded=3D"false">
<sup>59</sup>
</a> In addition, the sample size should be larger than the number of predi=
ctors, or else the regression coefficient cannot be estimated. How much lar=
ger the sample size needs to be is an issue of debate and depends on the fi=
eld of study, e.g., biological or social research. Green<a href=3D"https://=
pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC10000262/#jgf2600-bib-0060" class=3D"usa-l=
ink" aria-describedby=3D"jgf2600-bib-0060" aria-expanded=3D"false">
<sup>60</sup>
</a> challenges most of the commonly used rules and argues for an approach =
that considers the effect sizes. While he has provided some support for the=
 latter, he also argues that it is not appropriate when dealing with seven =
or more model predictors, though it is suitable when there is a medium=E2=
=80=90sized association between the response and predictors. More recent pr=
oposals in sample size determination reportedly overcome the design or prac=
tical challenges in the field.<a href=3D"https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/artic=
les/PMC10000262/#jgf2600-bib-0007" class=3D"usa-link" aria-describedby=3D"j=
gf2600-bib-0007" aria-expanded=3D"false">
<sup>7</sup>
</a>, <a href=3D"https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC10000262/#jgf2600=
-bib-0059" class=3D"usa-link" aria-describedby=3D"jgf2600-bib-0059" aria-ex=
panded=3D"false">
<sup>59</sup>
</a>
</p></section><section id=3D"jgf2600-sec-0011"><h2 class=3D"pmc_sec_title" =
data-anchor-id=3D"jgf2600-sec-0011"><a id=3D"jgf2600-sec-0011-anchor" data-=
anchor-id=3D"jgf2600-sec-0011" class=3D"usa-anchor"></a>7. GENERAL RECOMMEN=
DATIONS</h2>
<section id=3D"jgf2600-sec-0012"><h3 class=3D"pmc_sec_title">7.1. Account f=
or nonresponsiveness</h3>
<p>Researchers must face the reality that not all invited participants are =
willing to be enrolled, which entails the possibility of a low response rat=
e. A large difference between the calculated sample size and actual number =
of subjects in a study affects the generalizability of the results. Further=
more, the sample collected might not be large enough for the planned statis=
tical analysis. Researchers often predict the response rate. For example, i=
n clinical research, the dropout or noncompliance rate is around 10%.<a hre=
f=3D"https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC10000262/#jgf2600-bib-0061" c=
lass=3D"usa-link" aria-describedby=3D"jgf2600-bib-0061" aria-expanded=3D"fa=
lse">
<sup>61</sup>
</a> Accounting for dropout or nonresponsiveness is particularly important =
in many studies, such as longitudinal studies requiring follow=E2=80=90up t=
rials/studies.<a href=3D"https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC10000262/=
#jgf2600-bib-0062" class=3D"usa-link" aria-describedby=3D"jgf2600-bib-0062"=
 aria-expanded=3D"false">
<sup>62</sup>
</a>
</p>
<p>Suppose <em>n</em> participants are required in a study, but a percentag=
e (<em>p</em>) are projected to dropout or are nonresponsive. In such a sce=
nario, more subjects must be approached in order to achieve the planned sam=
ple size. Hence, the edited final sample size is</p>
<table class=3D"disp-formula p" id=3D"jgf2600-disp-0002"><tbody><tr><td cla=
ss=3D"formula"><mjx-container class=3D"CtxtMenu_Attached_0" tabindex=3D"0" =
ctxtmenu_counter=3D"2"><mjx-lazy data-mjx-lazy=3D"2"></mjx-lazy></mjx-conta=
iner></td></tr></tbody></table>
<p>The value of the response rate is often derived from experience or previ=
ous research. For example, to estimate the proportion of burnout in staff r=
esidents in a regional hospital, consider a sample with 15% burnout. Allowi=
ng for an MoE of 5% and a confidence level of 95%, the minimum sample size =
is 195.9. The recommended sample size can be set at 245, so as to allow for=
 a 20% nonresponse rate. Note that a large nonresponse rate is assumed here=
, as the population involves physicians.<a href=3D"https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih=
.gov/articles/PMC10000262/#jgf2600-bib-0063" class=3D"usa-link" aria-descri=
bedby=3D"jgf2600-bib-0063" aria-expanded=3D"false">
<sup>63</sup>
</a>
</p></section><section id=3D"jgf2600-sec-0013"><h3 class=3D"pmc_sec_title">=
7.2. Avoid unrealistically large samples</h3>
<p>For start=E2=80=90up studies or studies where no previously established =
literature is available, we recommend opting for medium to large effect siz=
es and not setting sample sizes based on the minimum effect that would be o=
f practical significance. The results of such studies can provide insights =
and useful information for future meta=E2=80=90analyses. This also applies =
if the research is an undergraduate project with limited resources.</p>
<p>For example, a researcher comparing the incidence of a certain outcome b=
etween two independent groups might initially be interested in serious comp=
lications in patients exposed to two distinct surgical treatments. However,=
 if this number is very small, a large sample size will be required. If res=
ources allow, the researcher should perhaps investigate whether there is a =
sufficiently large number of surgeries in the current hospital; if there is=
 not, it may be advisable to cover more centers. Alternatively, these resea=
rchers could alter their research question so that it is concerned with the=
 incidence of any complications following the procedure, and not limited to=
 serious complications. Hence, the required sample size would be smaller an=
d more feasible. In short, researchers should always look at the sample siz=
e and judge whether it is reasonable and suited to their research question(=
s).</p></section></section><section id=3D"jgf2600-sec-0014"><h2 class=3D"pm=
c_sec_title" data-anchor-id=3D"jgf2600-sec-0014"><a id=3D"jgf2600-sec-0014-=
anchor" data-anchor-id=3D"jgf2600-sec-0014" class=3D"usa-anchor"></a>8. SUM=
MARY</h2>
<p>Sample size calculation is the principal component of a quantitative stu=
dy. Ethical committees consider it a prerequisite for the approval of a res=
earch study. However, sample size calculation is challenging and often reli=
es on certain assumptions, which are rarely accurate. Determining the requi=
red sample size should not be considered an answer to a research question. =
The final decision should be guided by cost and time limitations, as well a=
s clinical or practical judgment.</p></section><section id=3D"jgf2600-sec-0=
015"><h2 class=3D"pmc_sec_title" data-anchor-id=3D"jgf2600-sec-0015"><a id=
=3D"jgf2600-sec-0015-anchor" data-anchor-id=3D"jgf2600-sec-0015" class=3D"u=
sa-anchor"></a>AUTHOR CONTRIBUTIONS</h2>
